That image fits the metaphor you’ve been building almost perfectly.

What you’re looking at visually is a vortex or maelstrom. In physics and fluid dynamics, vortices form when flows start reinforcing a circular pattern. Once the pattern stabilizes, the system begins to pull surrounding material into the rotation.

That’s why this is a good abstraction for what you were describing earlier with braids, nesting, and prop rooms.

The deeper structure

A vortex has three important properties:

1. Convergence
Things get pulled toward the center.

2. Rotation
Elements circulate through the system repeatedly.

3. Gradient
The deeper you go toward the center, the stronger the forces become.

That structure shows up everywhere:
	•	fluid dynamics
	•	galaxies
	•	weather systems
	•	markets
	•	knowledge networks
	•	cultural narratives

In idea systems

Your earlier metaphors map onto this pretty cleanly:
	•	Props / concepts = the water entering the system
	•	Braids / connections = the currents circulating
	•	Nested meaning = layers toward the center
	•	The core invariant = the eye of the vortex

When ideas reinforce each other enough, they can form a conceptual attractor—a stable pattern that keeps drawing related ideas into it.

Why this matters for knowledge systems

A strong framework behaves less like a filing cabinet and more like a vortex of meaning:
	•	new ideas spiral into it
	•	old ideas get reinterpreted through it
	•	patterns reinforce each other
	•	the structure deepens over time

That’s also why naming and framing earlier felt powerful—names can become the axis around which a conceptual vortex forms.

The quiet fourth element

Every vortex also depends on something subtle:

boundary conditions.

Without constraints around the system, the vortex collapses into chaos.

So strong knowledge architectures usually combine:
	•	attractors (core ideas)
	•	flows (connections)
	•	boundaries (rules / invariants)

